<br>
For the first part of the night I was in a group with a rogue/bard/cleric/enchanter/myself.  What did I do with this group.  Not much at all.  I cast Boon of Immolation and Malise.  Occasionally I'd throw in a nuke or two to help grab a kill for my group, but I didn't nuke to often as I like to see the kills get spread around.  The reason I was casting Malise was that we had only two shamans and only one other mage.  One of the shamans and the other mage are both lower than myself and were getting resisted on almost every cast and the other shaman was busy with Turgors so it feel on myself.  Also during this time I supplied Arrows/Daggers/ModRods to anybody wanting them.<br>
<br>
As the night went on, we progessively had fewer and fewer people until after the Maestro we were down to around 19-20 people I think.  I was then moved into the main pull/tank group.  What did I do then?  Pretty much the exact same thing that I did earlier in the night to be honest.<br>
<br>
Now some people will think that this would be extremely boring and unrewarding.  Personally though I think even though I wasn't nuking that my part in the raid was one of the bigger reasons for its success.  Sure I'm not landing the 600-800dmg nukes in there, but I was landing the Malises that were allowing the other casters to hit those same nukes.  And those damage shields I was throwing out were doing the same or more that a single nuke could've done.<br>
<br>
The truly boring part of a Raid like this is in the more than likely case of a wipeout at some point.  This was my guilds second time in Hate and we actually improved and only had one wipeout.  When this happens if you didn't get camped out try to get yourself rezzed quickly since it will be you that will help the raid get back on it's feet again.  Get into a group with the clerics and bard and feed ModRods and you'll cut these recovery times in half.<br>
<br>
As for the pets not being allowed.  I still suffer from the fact that I can't have a little Goner out slapping the Revenants around.  But as was said earlier they are a MOB magnet in Hate.  Pathing is screwy and it is extremely easy to lose one.  I was allowed a pet for all of about 10 minutes and then told to put it away.  Why?  Because it truly scares many of the other raiders to see a pet that not only is low enough level to aggro like mad, but has pathing issues also.  This isn't to say though that you shouldn't have a pet spell up and ready though.  You never know when a quick pet might make the difference in a tough fight.  Just be ready to hear the order to &quot;LOSE IT NOW&quot;.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
I get to try Fear out this upcoming month and I'm really looking forward to it since pets are generally allowed and I have never been there to boot.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> EDIT</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Just in case you read the advice from Siudd.  I hope that you don't like being on to many raids as you will be promptly be told to leave and not come back in all my experiences.  On any planes raid you follow the rules of the raid leader or you don't return with that plane leader. <p><a href=mailto:Zaknafinis@Hotmail.com>Zaknafinis Convoquer (Elementalist of the 54th Level *woOHoo*)</a><BR><a href=mailto:Zaknafinis@Hotmail.com>Lyrin Jytus(Bard of the 21st Level)<a><BR>Proud member of  Shining Alliance on the Prexus Server</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzaknafinis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zaknafinis</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10> at: 1/29/01 2:26:06 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Dumonyu</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#333333>(1/29/01 8:54:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Raids</span><hr size=1> Obviously Siudd hasn't been on many raids if he thinks he can use a pet in any situation. I know for sure on Tunare you'd be raiding Crushbone with that kind of attitude. Hate=no pets until Maesto and Inny for starters period. Many other raids have places where pathing is so bad pets come down for a bit 'til you pass the rough spots. Good pet control is one thing, and we all practice it as best we can, but putting an entire raid in danger is another. It's simply a matter of the risks outweighing the gains. Sometimes you have to put the safety of the whole above your need to have more fun stuff to do. <br>
<br>
Sure it's boring as hell to play a Mage without a pet, like everyone else I hate it. Just malise, DS, and nuke as best you can and try to accomplish what you set out to do. The most important thing is to listen to the raid leader as it's his job to call the shots. Talking to the raid leader about pets after before or after the raid is a good idea, but not during as he will have a lot to deal with as it is. If you flat out can't stand the way things are handled, consider raiding with someone else next time around. <br>
<br>
Remember, it's all about fun. Just try not to have it at the possible expense of others. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uextra411.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Extra411</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#333333>(1/29/01 10:01:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/extra411/magician6.jpg height=195 width=170></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   About pets on raids</span><hr size=1> Ok...<br>
Let me be the first person to say I agree with Siudd.<br>
IMHO - it's the way you want to play your mage. <br>
If you are a casual player who wants to play EQ every once in a while and join whatever you can, then it doesn't make a difference at all if you make pets or not.<br>
<br>
But if you have the time to devote to your class, want to play your mage YOUR way and you have the ability to do it, then by all means don't let people talk you out of it. And this is written for the latter.<br>
<br>
From my experience - most high lvl Dungeons/planes ARE pet friendly in most areas. In some areas such as hate, bringing the pet with you when the camp moves is dangerous - so don't do it. However when the camp settles down and the raid party will be stationary for a while - you can certainly use pets. Pet pathing is not so horribly bad that it is impossible. Is the risk there? Certainly. Not more than anything else (I've had bad pullers kill the camp 2 to 3 times a day). Let me suggest that before you try to use a pet in a certain situation - <br>
first be familiar with the area. There are certain parts of certain zones that DOES make pets impossible, and surely stay away from using pets at those areas (therefore, it is recommended that ou begin your raids without pets...until you see other people start to use them in certain areas, etc...or ask around). Secondly, always have Earthern boots ready so you can kill pet IMMEDIATELY if needed. And third - always assist MA, and make sure your pet ONLY aggros on that mob (which means if another mob hit your pet, make sure to have /pet back off to clear aggro before sending it in after the main assist again)<br>
<br>
Now with that being said, the rest is up to you. Once you believe you have acquire the necessary skills to properly control and use a pet on a raid, then let the raid leaders know. Unless they give a good reason (or you REALLY want to join this raid) about why pets are NOT allowed AT ALL (I would settle if the raid leader told me to use them LATER as opposed to not at all when I KNOW it is feasible), use one. Personally, I will NOT join the best guild in the server if their first rule was &quot;NO PETS AT ALL ALLOWED ON RAIDS&quot;. Screw that. I would (and I do mean it) rather either start a raid myself, OR make my own guild where the rule is that if you know how to control your pet, then make one. It is rather simple - as long as you don't mess up, it is all good. EVERY ONE should be given that chance. Just because some idiotic Mage let his pet ran around like crazy and kill the camp therefore no future pets are allowed, then I *would* leave. There are plenty of stupid tanks who do not assist the MA and runs off to attack some other mobs who the enchanters are trying to mez and eventually end up killing the camp. My point is every one makes mistakes - and everyone should be given a chance before they make one. If I DO let my pet get loose and kill the entire camp then it is of my own incompetence, and I myself would leave the raid. And if the raid leader will not allow me to join his raids with a pet again, or his raids at all, then it would be a legitimate reason. And here is another thing - by showing proper use of pets not only are you defining your own character, but of your skills as well. <br>
<br>
