<br>
A raid leader into the planes that says &quot;absolutely no pets&quot; just isn't a good leader.  If they were good/experienced they'd no when pets should be up and when they should be down.<br>
<br>
Not allowing pets is just bringing down the efficiency of the entire raiding party and showing the inexperience of the leaders.  <br>
<br>
There's no place in Hate that I've seen that had bad enough pathing that pets shouldn't be allowed.  They should always be taken down for moving to different locations unless its just a short hop, but most of the standard places to set up camp are pet friendly.  <br>
<br>
There are a couple of spots next to the walls where you have to be more pet concious.   There is one spot near the port-in that pets are sometimes disallowed.  You set up next to one of the 'bad' walls and a pet following a MoB up on a MoB could be trouble.   <br>
<br>
You could still have a pet out though.  You don't have to just target and hit pet attack.  Tapping pet attack then back off will have your pet attack for one round.  This is a controlled burst.  You just tap back and forth and anytime a MoB moves (and they tend to jump around a lot in the Planes) keep your pet backed off, move to where it went, and continue.  Never follow up walls or move past the edge of the camp spot.  <br>
<br>
I think its easier for raid leaders to call for no pets in some of these spots, but there really isn't a spot in Hate that I've seen that was so bad a pet can't be out and controlled.   Now, the side courtyard by the castle in the Hole has some bad pathing (unless its been fixed), but Hate isn't really that bad.<br>
<br>
Pets following MoBs that are running doesn't cause trains. The MoB is going to cause a train if not stopped regardless. Its the pet's path back to base camp that might cause trouble. Anytime a MoB takes off outside of the edge of where the group is camping you should back the pet off. Its just safer that way.  <br>
<br>
But, honestly, pets are usually more of a scape goat then anything else.  As many times as a pet caused a train there are just as many (if not more) that a player caused a train that got blamed on a pet.  <br>
<br>
Fear and Air I don't know so well so can't comment as much upon.   But, from what I understand, the same rules apply. Usually a pet is safe, you usually take them down for moving base camp, and there might be a spot or two where they aren't as safe, but for the most part they are. <br>
<br>
