<br>
Tips to good pet control....<br>
<br>
1)  In Hate us /pet sit down instead of /pet guard here.  That way, after the fight, the pet will not try to find its way back to you and get lost in pathing.  If pet is in a bad spot after fight, then /pet follow me, reposition, and /pet sit again.<br>
<br>
2)  Be aware of AoE spells casted by mobs.  Here is what happens...  You /assist and send pet to mob1.  Mob2 does an AoE before chanter mezzes it.  Mob1 dies, pet jumps on mob2 and breaks mez.  Lesson.... be aware of your pets aggro.  If you see a mob do AoE, then /pet back off, /assist, /pet attack.<br>
<br>
3) In a raid, or any situation where someone is mezzing, toggle your pet's taunt off with /pet taunt.  That will help the pet to NOT attract mobs when several are in camp, thus making like easier for the enchanter as pet won't get &quot;stuck&quot; on mobs.  If pet does gets stuck on a mob, /pet get lost immediately.  If is far better for you to have to resummon a pet, than for your pet to continuously break mez and earn your pet a bad reputation (which affects all Mages).<br>
<br>
I've been in hate before, and after only ONE TIME of a pet getting stuck and continuously breaking mez (which caused the chanters death) the leader called &quot;no pets&quot;.  One mage with bad pet control can screw all the pet classes there.  Your pet may do more damage than the tanks, may even save everyone's ass a time or two.....one time in hate me and another mage chain casted pets and saved a lot of peoples behinds.  Those stuns from air pets that interrupted that CH may have saved lives, but no one will praise the pets for such actions. BUT, it will only take one bad action to get him and other pets banished.<br>
<br>
Although some raid leaders will sometimes use &quot;bad pathing&quot; as the excuse for not allowing pets, I know that a lot of times it is not bad pathing, but more the fear that pets will break mez.<br>
